-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Matthew — Part 3 (Chapters 13–18)
-- 3 difficulties × 6 chapters = 96 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 18
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 30
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 48
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 13–15 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 13, 'kids', 1, 'In Jesus'' story about the sower, where did the good seed land that grew and produced fruit?', 'In the good ground', 'On the rocky ground', 'Among the thorns', 'On the path', 'a', 'Matthew 13:8 — "But other fell into good ground, and brought forth fruit, some an hundredfold, some sixtyfold, some thirtyfold."'),
('Matthew', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus compare the kingdom of heaven to that starts very small but grows very big?', 'A grain of mustard seed — the smallest of all seeds but it grows into the greatest among herbs and becomes a tree', 'A huge boulder', 'A tall building', 'A great army', 'a', 'Matthew 13:31-32 — "The kingdom of heaven is like to a grain of mustard seed... which indeed is the least of all seeds: but when it is grown, it is the greatest among herbs, and becometh a tree."'),
('Matthew', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What did the man in Jesus'' story do when he found treasure hidden in a field?', 'He went and sold all that he had and bought that field because he was so happy', 'He left it there and walked away', 'He told everyone about it', 'He was too afraid to dig it up', 'a', 'Matthew 13:44 — "The kingdom of heaven is like unto treasure hid in a field; the which when a man hath found, he hideth, and for joy thereof goeth and selleth all that he hath, and buyeth that field."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 13, 'teens', 1, 'What do the four types of soil represent in the parable of the sower?', 'Four different responses to God''s word: the path (hardened hearts that don''t understand), rocky ground (shallow faith that fades under pressure), thorny ground (faith choked by worldly cares and riches), and good ground (those who hear, understand, and bear fruit)', 'Four types of farming techniques', 'Four different seasons of the year', 'Four geographical regions of Israel', 'a', 'Matthew 13:18-23 — Jesus explains each soil: the wayside = lack of understanding (v.19), stony places = no root/temporary faith (v.20-21), thorns = cares of the world and deceitfulness of riches (v.22), good ground = understanding and fruit-bearing (v.23).'),
('Matthew', 13, 'teens', 2, 'Why did Jesus say He spoke in parables?', 'Because to the disciples it was given to know the mysteries of the kingdom, but to others it was not given — parables both reveal truth to seekers and conceal it from the hard-hearted', 'Because He could not think of anything else to say', 'Because parables were required by Jewish law', 'Because stories were easier than miracles', 'a', 'Matthew 13:11-13 — "Because it is given unto you to know the mysteries of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it is not given... Therefore speak I to them in parables: because they seeing see not; and hearing they hear not, neither do they understand."'),
('Matthew', 13, 'teens', 3, 'In the parable of the wheat and the tares, what did the master tell his servants about the weeds?', 'Let both grow together until the harvest, and at harvest time I will tell the reapers to gather the tares first and burn them, then gather the wheat into my barn', 'Pull out the weeds immediately', 'Ignore the weeds and only water the wheat', 'Plant more seeds to overcome the weeds', 'a', 'Matthew 13:30 — "Let both grow together until the harvest: and in the time of harvest I will say to the reapers, Gather ye together first the tares, and bind them in bundles to burn them: but gather the wheat into my barn."'),
('Matthew', 13, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus compare the kingdom of heaven to regarding a merchant seeking pearls?', 'A merchant who found one pearl of great price and sold all he had to buy it — the kingdom is worth everything', 'A merchant who collected many cheap pearls', 'A merchant who refused to sell anything', 'A merchant who only sold pearls to the rich', 'a', 'Matthew 13:45-46 — "The kingdom of heaven is like unto a merchant man, seeking goodly pearls: Who, when he had found one pearl of great price, went and sold all that he had, and bought it."'),
('Matthew', 13, 'teens', 5, 'Why did Jesus not do many mighty works in His hometown of Nazareth?', 'Because of their unbelief — they were offended by Him, saying "Is not this the carpenter''s son?"', 'Because He was too tired from travelling', 'Because the people were already healed', 'Because the Pharisees forbade it', 'a', 'Matthew 13:57-58 — "And they were offended in him... And he did not many mighty works there because of their unbelief."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 1, 'How does the parable of the sower function as the hermeneutical key to understanding all parables?', 'Jesus says "Know ye not this parable? and how then will ye know all parables?" (Mark 4:13). The sower parable establishes the fundamental principle: the word (seed) is constant; the variable is the human response (soil). All kingdom parables operate on this axis of human reception of divine truth', 'Each parable is completely independent', 'The sower parable is the least important', 'All parables teach the same lesson identically', 'a', 'Matthew 13:18-23 — The sower parable is foundational because it addresses why the kingdom message produces different results in different people. The same seed (word) encounters four soils (hearts). Understanding this dynamic — God sows identically but hearts respond differently — unlocks all kingdom teaching.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 2, 'What does Jesus'' citation of Isaiah 6:9-10 (13:14-15) teach about judicial hardening?', 'Isaiah''s "hearing but not understanding, seeing but not perceiving" describes both the consequence of persistent rejection and a divine judicial act — God confirms the hardness people have chosen. Parables serve this dual function: they illuminate the receptive and confirm the unresponsive in their blindness. Grace refused becomes judgment received', 'God arbitrarily blinds innocent people', 'Isaiah''s prophecy is unrelated to parables', 'Everyone who hears parables is automatically hardened', 'a', 'Matthew 13:14-15 — "By hearing ye shall hear, and shall not understand; and seeing ye shall see, and shall not perceive: For this people''s heart is waxed gross." The hardening is judicial (God confirms it) but not arbitrary (they chose it). Parables reveal this division: the same story opens some hearts and closes others.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 3, 'What does the parable of the wheat and tares teach about the church and premature judgment?', 'The kingdom on earth will contain both genuine believers (wheat) and counterfeit (tares/darnel, which looks like wheat until harvest). Jesus forbids premature separation — final sorting belongs to God at the end of the age. This counsels patience with the mixed state of the visible church and warns against overzealous purging', 'The church should aggressively excommunicate everyone suspicious', 'Tares and wheat are indistinguishable even at harvest', 'The parable is about literal agriculture', 'a', 'Matthew 13:24-30,36-43 — Tares (darnel/zizania) are nearly identical to wheat during growth, distinguishable only at harvest. "Lest while ye gather up the tares, ye root up also the wheat with them" (v.29). The separation at "the end of this world" (v.40) is God''s prerogative, not ours.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 4, 'What do the mustard seed and leaven parables teach about the kingdom''s growth pattern?', 'Both parables emphasise disproportionate growth from small beginnings — the mustard seed (smallest to greatest) shows external expansion, while leaven (working invisibly through dough) shows internal permeation. The kingdom starts inconspicuously but transforms everything it touches, eventually becoming comprehensive', 'The kingdom will always remain small', 'Leaven always represents evil in Scripture', 'These parables describe the kingdom shrinking', 'a', 'Matthew 13:31-33 — Mustard seed: external, visible, dramatic growth. Leaven: internal, invisible, pervasive influence. Together: the kingdom starts small (a carpenter from Nazareth, twelve disciples) but will ultimately fill the earth. The contrast between humble origins and ultimate triumph is the point.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 5, 'What do the hidden treasure and pearl of great price parables teach about the kingdom''s value?', 'Both parables teach that the kingdom is worth total sacrifice — but from different angles. The treasure is found accidentally (the kingdom finds some), while the pearl is found after diligent searching (some find the kingdom through seeking). In both cases, the finder joyfully surrenders everything because the kingdom''s value infinitely exceeds the cost', 'The kingdom can be purchased with money', 'Only wealthy people can enter the kingdom', 'These parables discourage generosity', 'a', 'Matthew 13:44-46 — "For joy thereof goeth and selleth all" — the sacrifice is joyful, not grudging. "All that he had" — the cost is total. The parables answer: "What is the kingdom worth?" Answer: everything you have and more. The joy of finding makes the cost seem trivial.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 6, 'What does the parable of the dragnet (13:47-50) teach about the final judgment?', 'Like a dragnet that catches every kind of fish and is sorted only when brought to shore, the kingdom message gathers all kinds of people, and separation occurs at "the end of the world" — angels will "sever the wicked from among the just." This parallels the wheat/tares parable but uses fishing imagery (appropriate for Galilean fishermen)', 'Fishing is the best way to evangelise', 'Only good people hear the gospel', 'Judgment happens immediately after conversion', 'a', 'Matthew 13:47-50 — "The kingdom of heaven is like unto a net, that was cast into the sea, and gathered of every kind: Which, when it was full, they drew to shore, and sat down, and gathered the good into vessels, but cast the bad away." The dragnet is indiscriminate; the sorting is eschatological.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 7, 'What does "every scribe which is instructed unto the kingdom of heaven is like unto a man that is an householder, which bringeth forth out of his treasure things new and old" mean?', 'A kingdom-trained disciple combines the old (Old Testament, traditional teaching) with the new (Jesus'' fresh revelation). Continuity and newness coexist: the old is not discarded but reinterpreted in light of Christ. This is Matthew''s own self-portrait as a Jewish scribe who became a kingdom disciple', 'Old things should be thrown away', 'Only new teaching matters', 'This describes a literal homeowner', 'a', 'Matthew 13:52 — "Things new and old." Matthew, a tax collector trained in Jewish tradition, exemplifies this: his Gospel draws on OT prophecy (old) and Jesus'' new revelation (new). The kingdom scribe treasures both, seeing how the old prepares for and is fulfilled by the new.'),
('Matthew', 13, 'adults', 8, 'Why is Jesus'' rejection at Nazareth (13:54-58) placed after the parables discourse?', 'The placement illustrates the sower parable in action — Nazareth represents the hard soil. Those most familiar with Jesus (His hometown) are the most offended. "A prophet is not without honour, save in his own country" shows that proximity does not guarantee receptivity. Familiarity breeds contempt, and unbelief limits even divine power ("He did not many mighty works there")', 'The placement is random', 'Nazareth was Jesus'' first preaching location', 'The people of Nazareth fully accepted Jesus', 'a', 'Matthew 13:57-58 — "A prophet is not without honour, save in his own country, and in his own house. And he did not many mighty works there because of their unbelief." Jesus'' unbelief did not limit His power but His willingness — He will not force miracles on the unwilling.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 14 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 14, 'kids', 1, 'How many people did Jesus feed with five loaves and two fishes?', 'About five thousand men, besides women and children', 'About one hundred people', 'Only the twelve disciples', 'About fifty people', 'a', 'Matthew 14:21 — "And they that had eaten were about five thousand men, beside women and children."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus do on the sea during a storm?', 'He walked on the water to the disciples'' boat', 'He swam to the other side', 'He flew over the water', 'He waited on the shore', 'a', 'Matthew 14:25 — "And in the fourth watch of the night Jesus went unto them, walking on the sea."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'kids', 3, 'What happened when Peter tried to walk on the water toward Jesus?', 'He started to sink when he saw the strong wind and was afraid, but Jesus caught him and said "O thou of little faith, wherefore didst thou doubt?"', 'He walked perfectly the whole way', 'He decided to stay in the boat', 'He swam instead of walking', 'a', 'Matthew 14:30-31 — "But when he saw the wind boisterous, he was afraid; and beginning to sink, he cried, saying, Lord, save me. And immediately Jesus stretched forth his hand, and caught him, and said unto him, O thou of little faith, wherefore didst thou doubt?"'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 14, 'teens', 1, 'Why was John the Baptist beheaded?', 'Herod arrested John for rebuking him about taking his brother Philip''s wife Herodias. At Herod''s birthday feast, Herodias'' daughter danced and pleased Herod, who promised her anything. Her mother told her to ask for John''s head on a platter', 'John had committed a crime against Rome', 'John tried to overthrow the government', 'John insulted the temple priests', 'a', 'Matthew 14:3-11 — "For Herod had laid hold on John, and bound him, and put him in prison for Herodias'' sake, his brother Philip''s wife. For John said unto him, It is not lawful for thee to have her."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus do before performing the miracle of feeding the five thousand?', 'He looked up to heaven, blessed the food, broke the loaves, and gave them to His disciples to distribute', 'He asked the people to go find their own food', 'He sent the disciples to buy bread in town', 'He told the crowd to go home', 'a', 'Matthew 14:19 — "He commanded the multitude to sit down on the grass, and took the five loaves, and the two fishes, and looking up to heaven, he blessed, and brake, and gave the loaves to his disciples, and the disciples to the multitude."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'teens', 3, 'How many baskets of leftovers were collected after the feeding of the five thousand?', 'Twelve baskets full of fragments', 'None — everything was eaten', 'Two baskets', 'Five baskets', 'a', 'Matthew 14:20 — "And they did all eat, and were filled: and they took up of the fragments that remained twelve baskets full."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'teens', 4, 'What did the disciples in the boat say when they saw Jesus walking on the sea?', 'They were troubled, saying "It is a spirit" — and they cried out for fear', 'They recognised Him immediately and waved', 'They ignored Him and kept rowing', 'They jumped into the water to meet Him', 'a', 'Matthew 14:26 — "And when the disciples saw him walking on the sea, they were troubled, saying, It is a spirit; and they cried out for fear."'),
('Matthew', 14, 'teens', 5, 'What did the disciples do after Jesus got into the boat and the wind ceased?', 'They came and worshipped Him, saying "Of a truth thou art the Son of God"', 'They asked Him to leave the boat', 'They pretended nothing had happened', 'They fell asleep immediately', 'a', 'Matthew 14:33 — "Then they that were in the ship came and worshipped him, saying, Of a truth thou art the Son of God."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 1, 'What does the feeding of the five thousand reveal about Jesus as the new Moses?', 'As Moses provided manna in the wilderness for Israel, Jesus provides bread in a desolate place for the multitude. The parallels are deliberate: a wilderness setting, miraculous provision, the people sitting in orderly groups (cf. Exodus 18:21). Jesus is the greater Moses who feeds not just a nation but all who come to Him', 'The feeding has no connection to Moses', 'Moses never provided food', 'The miracle was purely about compassion', 'a', 'Matthew 14:15-21 — The wilderness setting (eremos topos), miraculous bread, and satisfied multitude echo the Exodus. The twelve baskets may symbolise the twelve tribes of Israel. Jesus is the prophet like Moses (Deuteronomy 18:15) who provides for God''s people.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of twelve baskets of leftovers?', 'The twelve baskets likely symbolise the twelve tribes of Israel — there is more than enough provision for all God''s people. The abundance (more left over than was started with) demonstrates that God''s provision through Christ is not merely sufficient but superabundant. The God who fed Israel in the wilderness does so again through His Son', 'Twelve was coincidentally the number of baskets available', 'The number has no symbolic meaning', 'Twelve baskets represent the twelve apostles'' lunch', 'a', 'Matthew 14:20 — Twelve baskets (kophinoi, Jewish carrying baskets) — one for each tribe, suggesting Jesus provides for all Israel. The feeding points forward to the messianic banquet and backward to wilderness manna. Abundance, not scarcity, characterises kingdom provision.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 3, 'How does Jesus walking on the sea assert His divine identity?', 'In Job 9:8, God alone "treadeth upon the waves of the sea." In Psalm 77:19, "Thy way is in the sea, and thy path in the great waters." Jesus performing this act claims the prerogative of YHWH. His words "Be of good cheer; it is I" (ego eimi) echo God''s self-revelation "I AM" (Exodus 3:14)', 'Walking on water was a common miracle', 'It was a shallow sandbar', 'Jesus was floating, not walking', 'a', 'Matthew 14:25-27 — Jesus walks on the sea and says "It is I" (ego eimi). Job 9:8 identifies sea-treading as God''s exclusive act. The combination of walking on water + ego eimi constitutes a theophany — God manifesting Himself to His terrified people.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 4, 'What does Peter''s experience of walking on water and then sinking teach about faith?', 'Peter''s faith enabled the impossible (walking on water) but wavered when he shifted focus from Jesus to the threatening circumstances (wind). "O thou of little faith" does not mean no faith but divided focus. The lesson: faith is sustained not by ignoring circumstances but by fixing the gaze on Christ despite them', 'Peter had no faith at all', 'The wind literally blew Peter down', 'Peter was simply too heavy to float', 'a', 'Matthew 14:29-31 — Peter walked on water (genuine faith), then saw the wind (shifted focus), then sank (fear overtook faith), then cried out (turned back to Jesus), then was rescued (Jesus never let go). The sequence maps the anatomy of faith: fixation on Christ sustains, distraction by circumstances sinks.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 5, 'What is the literary and theological significance of the disciples'' confession "Of a truth thou art the Son of God" (14:33)?', 'This is the first time the disciples collectively call Jesus "Son of God" in Matthew — provoked by the nature miracles (feeding, sea-walking). It anticipates Peter''s great confession in 16:16 and the centurion''s declaration in 27:54. The confession emerges from witnessing divine acts that only God can perform', 'This confession was routine and unremarkable', 'The disciples were quoting a psalm', 'Only Peter made this confession', 'a', 'Matthew 14:33 — "Of a truth thou art the Son of God." Combined with worship (proskunesan), this is more than a compliment. The disciples have witnessed two back-to-back displays of divine power (feeding multitudes, walking on water) and draw the only logical conclusion.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 6, 'What does Herod''s murder of John the Baptist foreshadow about Jesus'' own fate?', 'John''s death at the hands of a weak ruler pressured by others prefigures Jesus'' death: both are innocent prophets killed by political authorities acting against their own judgment (Herod feared John; Pilate found no fault in Jesus). The narrative structure connects the forerunner''s end to the Messiah''s coming passion', 'John''s death is unrelated to Jesus'' story', 'Herod was a righteous ruler', 'John died of natural causes', 'a', 'Matthew 14:1-12 — John''s martyrdom foreshadows Jesus'' passion: innocent prophet, unjust trial, weak ruler, political pressure. Matthew places this narrative before Jesus'' miracles, creating a contrast: the world kills God''s prophets while God multiplies bread and walks on storms.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 7, 'Why does Jesus withdraw to a "desert place apart" (14:13) after hearing of John''s death?', 'Jesus'' withdrawal reflects genuine human grief at His forerunner''s murder, but also a pattern of retreating for prayer and preparation (cf. 14:23). The withdrawal is interrupted by the crowds, and Jesus'' compassion overcomes His need for solitude — He heals and feeds them. This shows the integration of His human emotion and divine mission', 'Jesus was afraid Herod would kill Him', 'He needed to plan a political response', 'The withdrawal was a strategic military move', 'a', 'Matthew 14:13-14 — "When Jesus heard of it, he departed thence by ship into a desert place apart: and when the people had heard thereof, they followed him... he was moved with compassion toward them, and he healed their sick." Grief gives way to compassion; personal loss does not halt His mission.'),
('Matthew', 14, 'adults', 8, 'What does Jesus'' command "Bring them hither to me" (14:18) teach about how God uses inadequate resources?', 'The disciples saw the five loaves and two fish as hopelessly inadequate. Jesus'' response was not to create food from nothing but to take what little was offered, bless it, and multiply it. God works through surrendered insufficiency, not through human sufficiency — the little that is given to Jesus becomes more than enough', 'Jesus only works with large resources', 'The food was already sufficient before the miracle', 'Jesus created food from nothing', 'a', 'Matthew 14:17-18 — "We have here but five loaves, and two fishes. He said, Bring them hither to me." The pattern: admit insufficiency, bring what you have to Jesus, let Him bless and multiply. God''s power + human offering = abundance. This is the paradigm for all Christian ministry.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 15 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 15, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say makes a person unclean — what goes into the mouth or what comes out?', 'Not what goes into the mouth but what comes out of the mouth defiles a man — because evil words come from the heart', 'Only what you eat makes you unclean', 'Both are equally wrong', 'Neither one matters', 'a', 'Matthew 15:11 — "Not that which goeth into the mouth defileth a man; but that which cometh out of the mouth, this defileth a man."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'kids', 2, 'How many people did Jesus feed the second time with seven loaves and a few fishes?', 'Four thousand men, besides women and children', 'Five thousand men', 'One thousand people', 'One hundred people', 'a', 'Matthew 15:38 — "And they that did eat were four thousand men, beside women and children."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'kids', 3, 'What did the Canaanite woman keep asking Jesus to do?', 'Have mercy on her and heal her daughter who was vexed with a devil', 'Give her money for food', 'Make her daughter a disciple', 'Build a house for her family', 'a', 'Matthew 15:22 — "Have mercy on me, O Lord, thou Son of David; my daughter is grievously vexed with a devil."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 15, 'teens', 1, 'Why did Jesus rebuke the Pharisees about their tradition of "Corban"?', 'They used a tradition that allowed people to dedicate their money to God (Corban) as an excuse not to financially support their parents — thus making the word of God of none effect by their tradition', 'He objected to all religious traditions', 'He wanted people to stop giving to the temple', 'He thought the Pharisees were too generous', 'a', 'Matthew 15:5-6 — "But ye say, Whosoever shall say to his father or his mother, It is a gift, by whatsoever thou mightest be profited by me; And honour not his father or his mother, he shall be free. Thus have ye made the commandment of God of none effect by your tradition."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus list as the evil things that come from the heart?', 'Evil thoughts, murders, adulteries, fornications, thefts, false witness, and blasphemies', 'Only anger and hatred', 'Only dishonesty', 'Only laziness and pride', 'a', 'Matthew 15:19 — "For out of the heart proceed evil thoughts, murders, adulteries, fornications, thefts, false witness, blasphemies."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'teens', 3, 'What clever answer did the Canaanite woman give Jesus about the children''s bread?', 'Truth, Lord: yet the dogs eat of the crumbs which fall from their masters'' table — even the scraps of God''s mercy would be enough to heal her daughter', 'She said she deserved a full meal', 'She said dogs should eat first', 'She walked away offended', 'a', 'Matthew 15:27 — "And she said, Truth, Lord: yet the dogs eat of the crumbs which fall from their masters'' table."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say about the Pharisees after the disciples reported they were offended?', 'Every plant which my heavenly Father hath not planted shall be rooted up. Let them alone: they be blind leaders of the blind. If the blind lead the blind, both shall fall into the ditch', 'We should apologise to them', 'They are the most important religious leaders', 'We must always obey the Pharisees', 'a', 'Matthew 15:13-14 — "Every plant, which my heavenly Father hath not planted, shall be rooted up. Let them alone: they be blind leaders of the blind. And if the blind lead the blind, both shall fall into the ditch."'),
('Matthew', 15, 'teens', 5, 'How did Jesus respond to the Canaanite woman''s persistent faith?', 'O woman, great is thy faith: be it unto thee even as thou wilt — and her daughter was made whole from that very hour', 'He ignored her request completely', 'He told her to come back another day', 'He asked the disciples to send her away', 'a', 'Matthew 15:28 — "Then Jesus answered and said unto her, O woman, great is thy faith: be it unto thee even as thou wilt. And her daughter was made whole from that very hour."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 1, 'How does Jesus'' teaching on defilement (15:10-20) revolutionise the biblical purity system?', 'Jesus relocates defilement from external contact (food, objects, people) to internal disposition (the heart). This does not abolish the distinction between clean and unclean but reveals its deepest meaning: moral impurity, not ritual impurity, is the real problem. Mark 7:19 explicitly adds "purging all meats," showing the radical implication', 'Jesus supported the existing purity laws fully', 'External purity is more important than internal', 'Jesus only discussed food allergies', 'a', 'Matthew 15:17-20 — "Whatsoever entereth in at the mouth goeth into the belly... But those things which proceed out of the mouth come forth from the heart; and they defile the man." Jesus inverts the purity paradigm: the heart is the source of defilement, not the stomach.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 2, 'What is the theological significance of Jesus'' encounter with the Canaanite woman?', 'This encounter tests and demonstrates faith that transcends ethnic boundaries. Jesus'' initial silence and apparent refusal ("I am not sent but unto the lost sheep of the house of Israel") heighten the tension to showcase the woman''s extraordinary faith. Her persistence and humility result in the only person in Matthew whom Jesus praises with "great is thy faith"', 'Jesus was genuinely refusing to help Gentiles', 'The story shows Jesus changing His mind about Gentiles', 'The woman had no real faith', 'a', 'Matthew 15:22-28 — The woman''s faith overcomes every obstacle: silence (v.23), apparent rejection (v.24), and cultural insult (v.26 "dogs"). Her response (v.27) shows humble, tenacious trust — she does not challenge the priority of Israel but claims even the crumbs of God''s mercy are sufficient. Jesus commends "great" (megale) faith.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 3, 'What does Jesus'' phrase "It is not meet to take the children''s bread, and to cast it to dogs" mean, and is it a genuine insult?', 'Jesus uses "dogs" (kunarion = little dogs/household pets, not wild street dogs) — a common Jewish metaphor for Gentiles. He is not insulting but testing her faith by articulating the salvation-historical priority. His use of the diminutive form (puppies, not dogs) softens the language, and the woman''s response shows she understood the test and passed brilliantly', 'Jesus was being deliberately cruel', 'The word "dogs" had no cultural significance', 'Jesus was quoting a Roman proverb', 'a', 'Matthew 15:26 — "Kunarion" (little dogs/puppies) is the diminutive, not "kuon" (wild dogs). The household setting (children at table, pets beneath) creates an opening the woman seizes: even pets receive scraps from the master''s table. Jesus set up the metaphor knowing she would complete it with faith.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 4, 'How does Jesus'' confrontation with the Pharisees over tradition vs. commandment (15:1-9) address the perennial tension between Scripture and tradition?', 'Jesus establishes an absolute hierarchy: the commandment of God supersedes all human traditions. When tradition contradicts Scripture (as Corban nullified the fifth commandment), tradition must yield. The quotation of Isaiah 29:13 ("their heart is far from me") diagnoses the root problem: external religious performance without internal devotion', 'Tradition is always equal to Scripture', 'All traditions are wrong', 'The Pharisees had no traditions', 'a', 'Matthew 15:3,6,8-9 — "Why do ye also transgress the commandment of God by your tradition?... Thus have ye made the commandment of God of none effect by your tradition... in vain they do worship me, teaching for doctrines the commandments of men." The principle: tradition serves Scripture, never supersedes it.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 5, 'What does the feeding of the four thousand add to the feeding of the five thousand?', 'The two feedings serve different audiences: the five thousand occurred in Jewish territory (twelve baskets = twelve tribes), while the four thousand occurred in Gentile/Decapolis territory (seven baskets = seven Canaanite nations or completeness). Together, they show Jesus as the bread of life for both Jews and Gentiles', 'The second feeding is a doublet of the first', 'Jesus forgot He had already done this miracle', 'The numbers have no significance', 'a', 'Matthew 15:32-38 — The location (near Decapolis, Gentile territory), seven baskets (spurides, large hampers vs. twelve kophinoi), and four thousand (vs. five thousand) all differ. Jesus feeds both Israel and the nations, previewing the universal scope of His mission (cf. 28:19).'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 6, 'What does Jesus'' quote of Isaiah 29:13 reveal about the nature of hypocrisy?', 'Hypocrisy is the gap between lip-service and heart-devotion — honouring God with words while the heart is far from Him. The Pharisees'' elaborate external practices masked internal distance from God. True worship requires the unity of outward expression and inward reality — when these diverge, worship becomes vain (maten)', 'Hypocrisy is a minor character flaw', 'Isaiah was not speaking about future religious leaders', 'The Pharisees were sincere in their worship', 'a', 'Matthew 15:8-9 — "This people draweth nigh unto me with their mouth, and honoureth me with their lips; but their heart is far from me. But in vain they do worship me." The diagnosis: the problem is not insufficient religion but insincere religion — proximity of lips without proximity of heart.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 7, 'How does Jesus'' statement "Let them alone: they be blind leaders of the blind" guide responses to false teaching?', 'Jesus counsels disengagement from persistent, incorrigible false teachers — not endless debate but strategic withdrawal. The blind-leading-blind metaphor warns that following false teachers leads to shared destruction (both fall into the ditch). Discernment means knowing when to engage and when to leave false teachers to their own devices', 'Christians should always debate false teachers', 'All religious leaders are blind', 'Blindness refers to physical disability', 'a', 'Matthew 15:14 — "Let them alone: they be blind leaders of the blind." Jesus does not say "argue with them endlessly" but "let them alone." The Pharisees'' blindness is wilful (12:24, attributing miracles to Satan) — beyond the point where argument helps. Sometimes the most faithful response is walking away.'),
('Matthew', 15, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of Jesus healing multitudes on a mountain in Gentile territory (15:29-31)?', 'The people "glorified the God of Israel" (15:31) — a phrase that only makes sense if the crowd is predominantly Gentile. Jesus on a mountain healing the lame, blind, dumb, and maimed echoes Isaiah 35:5-6 (messianic healing) extended to the nations. The Messiah''s compassion reaches beyond Israel''s borders', 'The mountain location is insignificant', 'All the people were Jewish', 'These healings did not really happen', 'a', 'Matthew 15:30-31 — "And they glorified the God of Israel." This phrase implies a non-Israelite audience — Jews would simply say "God," not "the God of Israel." Jesus'' ministry in Gentile territory fulfils Isaiah''s vision of the Messiah blessing all nations.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 16–18 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 16 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 16, 'kids', 1, 'What did Peter say when Jesus asked "Who do you say that I am?"', 'Thou art the Christ, the Son of the living God', 'You are a good teacher', 'You are John the Baptist', 'You are one of the prophets', 'a', 'Matthew 16:16 — "And Simon Peter answered and said, Thou art the Christ, the Son of the living God."'),
('Matthew', 16, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus say He would build, and the gates of hell would not prevail against it?', 'His church', 'A great temple', 'A golden palace', 'A mighty army', 'a', 'Matthew 16:18 — "Upon this rock I will build my church; and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it."'),
('Matthew', 16, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus tell His disciples they must do to follow Him?', 'Deny themselves, take up their cross, and follow Him', 'Become rich and powerful first', 'Never leave their homes', 'Only pray and fast', 'a', 'Matthew 16:24 — "If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross, and follow me."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 16, 'teens', 1, 'What did Jesus say to the Pharisees and Sadducees when they asked for a sign from heaven?', 'A wicked and adulterous generation seeketh after a sign; and there shall no sign be given unto it, but the sign of the prophet Jonas', 'He immediately showed them a miracle', 'He promised to return with a sign next week', 'He agreed they deserved a special sign', 'a', 'Matthew 16:4 — "A wicked and adulterous generation seeketh after a sign; and there shall no sign be given unto it, but the sign of the prophet Jonas."'),
('Matthew', 16, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus warn His disciples to beware of?', 'The leaven (teaching) of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees — their false doctrine that spreads like yeast through dough', 'Literal bread and yeast', 'The Romans'' military strategy', 'Fishing in dangerous waters', 'a', 'Matthew 16:11-12 — "How is it that ye do not understand that I spake it not to you concerning bread, that ye should beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees?... Then understood they how that he bade them not beware of the leaven of bread, but of the doctrine."'),
('Matthew', 16, 'teens', 3, 'What did Jesus say to Peter when Peter rebuked Him for predicting His death?', 'Get thee behind me, Satan: thou art an offence unto me: for thou savourest not the things that be of God, but those that be of men', 'Thank you for caring about me, Peter', 'You are right, I should not suffer', 'Let us discuss this more later', 'a', 'Matthew 16:23 — "But he turned, and said unto Peter, Get thee behind me, Satan: thou art an offence unto me: for thou savourest not the things that be of God, but those that be of men."'),
('Matthew', 16, 'teens', 4, 'What did Jesus say about the value of a person''s soul?', 'What is a man profited, if he shall gain the whole world, and lose his own soul? Or what shall a man give in exchange for his soul?', 'The soul is not very valuable', 'Material wealth is more important than the soul', 'The soul and the world are worth the same', 'a', 'Matthew 16:26 — "For what is a man profited, if he shall gain the whole world, and lose his own soul? or what shall a man give in exchange for his soul?"'),
('Matthew', 16, 'teens', 5, 'What did Jesus first tell His disciples about His future?', 'He must go to Jerusalem, suffer many things from the elders, chief priests, and scribes, be killed, and be raised again the third day', 'He would become king of Israel', 'He would travel to Rome', 'He would retire to Nazareth', 'a', 'Matthew 16:21 — "From that time forth began Jesus to shew unto his disciples, how that he must go unto Jerusalem, and suffer many things of the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and be raised again the third day."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 1, 'What does "upon this rock I will build my church" refer to — Peter, his confession, or Christ Himself?', 'The most likely interpretation integrates all three: "Peter" (Petros) is the rock (petra) in his representative role as the first to confess Jesus as Messiah. The foundation is Peter''s confession of Christ — and by extension, all who make the same confession. The church is built on the Christ whom Peter confessed, with Peter as the foundational spokesperson', 'The rock is literally a physical stone', 'Only Peter personally is the foundation', 'The rock has nothing to do with Peter', 'a', 'Matthew 16:18 — "Thou art Peter (Petros), and upon this rock (petra) I will build my church." The wordplay connects Peter to the rock. In Ephesians 2:20, the church is built on "apostles and prophets, Jesus Christ himself being the chief corner stone." Peter is foundational as a confessor of Christ, not as an independent authority.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 2, 'What are "the keys of the kingdom of heaven" and the power of binding and loosing?', 'Keys represent authority to open the kingdom through gospel proclamation (cf. Acts 2, Peter opens the kingdom at Pentecost). "Binding and loosing" was rabbinic language for declaring what is forbidden or permitted — authoritative interpretation and discipline. This authority extends to all apostles (18:18) and is exercised through Spirit-guided community discernment', 'Literal metal keys to a gate', 'The power to lock people out of heaven permanently', 'Only Peter''s personal authority with no succession', 'a', 'Matthew 16:19 — "I will give unto thee the keys of the kingdom of heaven: and whatsoever thou shalt bind on earth shall be bound in heaven." Keys = authority to open/declare (Isaiah 22:22). Binding/loosing = authoritative teaching about what is prohibited/permitted (cf. 18:18, given to the whole church).'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 3, 'Why does Jesus call Peter "Satan" immediately after blessing him?', 'Peter shifts from being the mouthpiece of the Father (v.17 "flesh and blood hath not revealed it unto thee") to being the mouthpiece of Satan (v.23 "thou savourest not the things that be of God"). The same disciple can speak divine truth one moment and satanic error the next. Peter''s temptation mirrors Satan''s in chapter 4: offering a crown without a cross', 'Jesus was angry at Peter permanently', 'Peter was actually possessed by Satan', 'Jesus used the word casually as an insult', 'a', 'Matthew 16:17,23 — The contrast is stunning: "Blessed art thou, Simon" (v.17) → "Get thee behind me, Satan" (v.23). Peter tries to deflect Jesus from the cross — the same temptation Satan offered (4:8-9, kingdoms without suffering). The cross is non-negotiable; any theology without it is satanic.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 4, 'What does "take up his cross" mean in context, before the crucifixion has occurred?', 'For Jesus'' original audience, a cross was not a religious symbol but a Roman instrument of execution. Taking up one''s cross meant being willing to face public shame, suffering, and death — like a condemned criminal carrying his crossbeam to execution. Jesus is demanding willingness to die rather than deny Him', 'It meant carrying a piece of wood for exercise', 'It was a metaphor for minor inconveniences', 'The phrase had no meaning before the crucifixion', 'a', 'Matthew 16:24 — "Let him deny himself, and take up his cross, and follow me." In the Roman world, condemned prisoners carried their crossbeam to the execution site. Jesus'' audience would have understood this as: "Be willing to go to your death for Me." It was shockingly literal, not vaguely metaphorical.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 5, 'How does "flesh and blood hath not revealed it unto thee, but my Father which is in heaven" establish the source of saving faith?', 'True recognition of Christ does not originate in human reasoning, education, or intuition but in divine revelation. Peter''s confession was not the product of his own insight but a gift from the Father. This establishes that saving faith is supernaturally given, not humanly generated — a theme Paul develops in Ephesians 2:8-9', 'Peter figured it out by himself', 'The other disciples told Peter what to say', 'Jesus was complimenting Peter''s intelligence', 'a', 'Matthew 16:17 — "Blessed art thou, Simon Barjona: for flesh and blood hath not revealed it unto thee, but my Father which is in heaven." The source of Peter''s confession is divine revelation. Human reasoning alone ("flesh and blood") cannot produce saving faith — it requires God''s illuminating work.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological significance of the word "must" (dei) in verse 21?', 'The Greek "dei" (it is necessary/must) indicates divine necessity, not mere inevitability — Jesus'' suffering, death, and resurrection are not tragic accidents but the predetermined plan of God. This "divine must" appears throughout the passion predictions and establishes the cross as central to God''s purpose, not a plan B', 'The word "must" is incidental to the passage', 'Jesus was expressing personal desire', 'The suffering was optional', 'a', 'Matthew 16:21 — "From that time forth began Jesus to shew unto his disciples, how that he must (dei) go unto Jerusalem, and suffer... and be killed, and be raised again." The divine necessity (dei) frames the passion as God''s predetermined will (cf. Acts 2:23, "determinate counsel"). The cross was Plan A.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 7, 'What does "the gates of hell shall not prevail against it" promise about the church?', 'Gates are defensive structures — "the gates of hell (hades)" represents death''s power to hold its captives. Jesus promises that death itself cannot withstand the church''s advance. This is an offensive promise: the church storms the gates of death, empowered by the resurrection. The church is not merely surviving but conquering', 'The church will just barely survive', 'Gates of hell represents Satan attacking the church', 'The church will need human protection', 'a', 'Matthew 16:18 — "The gates of hell shall not prevail against it." Gates do not attack; they defend. The imagery is of the church besieging the fortress of death/hades — and winning. Christ''s resurrection broke death''s gates (cf. Acts 2:24, "it was not possible that he should be holden of it"), and the church continues this victory.'),
('Matthew', 16, 'adults', 8, 'How does verse 28 ("some standing here... shall not taste of death, till they see the Son of man coming in his kingdom") relate to the Transfiguration?', 'The immediate literary context connects this promise to the Transfiguration (17:1-8), which follows six days later. Peter, James, and John witness Jesus'' glory — a preview of His kingdom coming in power. This is a proleptic (anticipatory) vision of the second coming glory, fulfilling the promise without exhausting its ultimate eschatological meaning', 'Jesus was predicting the second coming within a generation', 'The verse is an unfulfilled prophecy', 'This has no connection to the Transfiguration', 'a', 'Matthew 16:28 — "Some standing here... shall not taste of death, till they see the Son of man coming in his kingdom." Six days later (17:1), three disciples witness Jesus'' transfigured glory. Peter himself connects the two in 2 Peter 1:16-18: "We... were eyewitnesses of his majesty" at the Transfiguration.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 17 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 17, 'kids', 1, 'What happened to Jesus on the high mountain in front of Peter, James, and John?', 'His face shone like the sun and His clothes became white as the light — He was transfigured', 'He disappeared completely', 'He grew very tall', 'He changed into an angel', 'a', 'Matthew 17:2 — "And was transfigured before them: and his face did shine as the sun, and his raiment was white as the light."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'kids', 2, 'Which two Old Testament people appeared and talked with Jesus on the mountain?', 'Moses and Elias (Elijah)', 'Abraham and David', 'Noah and Joshua', 'Samuel and Daniel', 'a', 'Matthew 17:3 — "And, behold, there appeared unto them Moses and Elias talking with him."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say about faith the size of a mustard seed?', 'If you have faith as a grain of mustard seed, you could say unto this mountain, Remove hence to yonder place, and it shall remove — nothing shall be impossible unto you', 'Even mustard seed faith is too small', 'Mountains cannot ever be moved', 'Only big faith can do anything', 'a', 'Matthew 17:20 — "If ye have faith as a grain of mustard seed, ye shall say unto this mountain, Remove hence to yonder place; and it shall remove; and nothing shall be impossible unto you."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 17, 'teens', 1, 'What did the voice from the cloud say during the Transfiguration?', 'This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased; hear ye him', 'This is a great prophet, listen carefully', 'This is the king of the world', 'Do not be afraid of the light', 'a', 'Matthew 17:5 — "While he yet spake, behold, a bright cloud overshadowed them: and behold a voice out of the cloud, which said, This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased; hear ye him."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'teens', 2, 'What did Jesus say about Elijah when the disciples asked about him?', 'Elias is come already, and they knew him not, but have done unto him whatsoever they listed — referring to John the Baptist', 'Elijah never came and never will', 'Elijah is still in heaven waiting', 'Elijah was just a legend', 'a', 'Matthew 17:12-13 — "But I say unto you, That Elias is come already, and they knew him not... Then the disciples understood that he spake unto them of John the Baptist."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'teens', 3, 'Why could the disciples not cast out the demon from the boy at the foot of the mountain?', 'Because of their unbelief — Jesus said this kind does not go out but by prayer and fasting', 'Because demons cannot be cast out', 'Because the boy did not want to be healed', 'Because it was the wrong time of day', 'a', 'Matthew 17:20-21 — "Jesus said unto them, Because of your unbelief... Howbeit this kind goeth not out but by prayer and fasting."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'teens', 4, 'How did Jesus pay the temple tax for Himself and Peter?', 'He told Peter to go fishing and take the first fish he caught — a coin (a piece of money/stater) would be in its mouth, enough for both of them', 'He borrowed money from the disciples', 'He asked the temple for a discount', 'He refused to pay the tax', 'a', 'Matthew 17:27 — "Go thou to the sea, and cast an hook, and take up the fish that first cometh up; and when thou hast opened his mouth, thou shalt find a piece of money: that take, and give unto them for me and thee."'),
('Matthew', 17, 'teens', 5, 'What did the father of the demon-possessed boy say about his son''s condition?', 'Lord, have mercy on my son: for he is lunatick, and sore vexed: for ofttimes he falleth into the fire, and oft into the water', 'My son has a minor headache', 'My son refuses to eat vegetables', 'My son does not like going to school', 'a', 'Matthew 17:15 — "Lord, have mercy on my son: for he is lunatick, and sore vexed: for ofttimes he falleth into the fire, and oft into the water."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological significance of Moses and Elijah appearing with Jesus at the Transfiguration?', 'Moses represents the Law and Elijah represents the Prophets — the two divisions of the Old Testament. Their appearance with the glorified Jesus shows that the entire Old Testament points to and is fulfilled in Christ. The Father''s command "hear ye him" transfers ultimate authority from Law and Prophets to the Son', 'They appeared randomly with no significance', 'They represented two political parties', 'They were angels disguised as Moses and Elijah', 'a', 'Matthew 17:3-5 — Moses (Law-giver) + Elijah (greatest prophet) + Jesus = the entire revelation of God. The Father''s voice ("hear ye him") echoes Deuteronomy 18:15 ("a Prophet... unto him ye shall hearken"), transferring the listen-command from Torah to Christ.'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 2, 'How does the Transfiguration function as a preview of the Second Coming?', 'Peter himself interprets the Transfiguration as a preview of Christ''s "power and coming" (2 Peter 1:16-18). The elements match eschatological imagery: glorified body, bright cloud (Shekinah), heavenly voice, and appearing with OT saints. It temporarily lifts the veil of Jesus'' humanity to reveal the glory hidden beneath', 'The Transfiguration was a hallucination', 'It has no connection to future events', 'The Second Coming will be nothing like the Transfiguration', 'a', 'Matthew 17:1-8 — The Transfiguration reveals what the resurrection and return will fully display: Jesus'' inherent divine glory. The "face shining as the sun" anticipates Revelation 1:16; the "bright cloud" recalls the Exodus pillar (Exodus 13:21) and the eschatological cloud (Daniel 7:13).'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 3, 'What does Peter''s suggestion to build three tabernacles reveal about his misunderstanding?', 'Peter wanted to prolong the mountaintop experience and equalise Moses, Elijah, and Jesus as three parallel figures worth commemorating. The Father''s interruption ("This is my beloved Son... hear ye him") corrects this by establishing Jesus'' supremacy. Moses and Elijah are witnesses; Jesus is the Lord they point to', 'Peter''s suggestion was perfectly appropriate', 'Building tabernacles was a Jewish requirement', 'Peter was being deliberately disrespectful', 'a', 'Matthew 17:4 — "Lord, it is good for us to be here: if thou wilt, let us make here three tabernacles." Peter places Jesus alongside Moses and Elijah (three tabernacles = three equals). God''s response rejects this: only one voice matters — "hear ye him." Jesus is not one among equals but the unique Son.'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 4, 'What does "this kind goeth not out but by prayer and fasting" teach about spiritual warfare?', 'Some spiritual challenges require deeper dependence on God than others — not all demons (or spiritual obstacles) yield to the same level of faith. Prayer and fasting represent intensified reliance on God, acknowledging that some battles require a depth of communion with God that casual faith does not achieve', 'All demons are equally easy to cast out', 'Prayer and fasting are merely dietary practices', 'This verse was Jesus'' only teaching on spiritual warfare', 'a', 'Matthew 17:21 — "Howbeit this kind goeth not out but by prayer and fasting." The disciples'' failure (v.16) stemmed from "unbelief" (v.20) — insufficient spiritual preparation. Prayer and fasting are not magical formulas but disciplines that cultivate the deep-faith relationship with God that overcomes the most entrenched spiritual opposition.'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 5, 'How does Jesus'' second passion prediction (17:22-23) develop beyond the first (16:21)?', 'The second prediction adds "The Son of man shall be betrayed into the hands of men" — introducing the element of human betrayal, not just religious opposition. The disciples'' sorrow (v.23) shows they are beginning to understand, unlike Peter''s rebuke in 16:22. Each prediction deepens the disciples'' preparation for the cross', 'The two predictions are identical', 'The second prediction removes the resurrection', 'The disciples ignored this prediction', 'a', 'Matthew 17:22-23 — "The Son of man shall be betrayed into the hands of men: And they shall kill him, and the third day he shall be raised again. And they were exceeding sorry." "Betrayed" (paradidosthai) is new — adding human treachery to the suffering portrait. The progression: 16:21 (elders/priests/scribes); 17:22 (betrayal); 20:18-19 (Gentiles, crucifixion).'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 6, 'What does the temple tax episode (17:24-27) teach about Jesus'' identity and His voluntary submission?', 'Jesus is the Son of the King (God) and therefore exempt from the temple tax (just as kings'' children are exempt from their own taxes). Yet He pays "lest we should offend them" — voluntarily submitting to avoid unnecessary scandal. This reveals both His divine sonship (He is exempt) and His humility (He submits anyway)', 'Jesus was required to pay like everyone else', 'Jesus refused to pay the tax', 'The miracle of the fish-coin is unimportant', 'a', 'Matthew 17:25-27 — "Of whom do the kings of the earth take custom... of their own children, or of strangers?... Then are the children free." Jesus is the Son of the temple''s Owner — therefore free. But He pays to avoid offence. The coin in the fish''s mouth demonstrates His lordship over creation even while voluntarily submitting.'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 7, 'What does "nothing shall be impossible unto you" (17:20) teach about the relationship between faith and divine power?', 'Faith does not generate power independently — it connects the believer to God''s omnipotence. Even "mustard seed" faith (the smallest amount) is sufficient because faith''s power lies not in its quantity but in the God to whom it is directed. Mountain-moving is not about human willpower but about trusting an all-powerful God', 'Larger faith produces more miracles', 'Faith is a measurable substance', 'This promise is hyperbolic and not real', 'a', 'Matthew 17:20 — "If ye have faith as a grain of mustard seed... nothing shall be impossible unto you." The mustard seed is proverbially the smallest seed. Even tiny faith moves mountains because it connects to infinite power. The issue is not the size of faith but the size of the God faith trusts.'),
('Matthew', 17, 'adults', 8, 'How does the descent from the Transfiguration mountain parallel Moses'' descent from Sinai?', 'Both Moses and Jesus descend from a mountain of divine glory to find God''s people in a state of failure — Moses found the golden calf (Exodus 32), Jesus found the disciples unable to cast out a demon (17:14-16). The parallel reinforces Jesus as the new Moses, but where Moses'' face merely reflected glory, Jesus''s face was the source of glory', 'There is no parallel between the two events', 'Moses never went up a mountain', 'Jesus was angry like Moses', 'a', 'Matthew 17:14-16 — Both descents move from divine glory to human failure. Moses: Sinai glory → golden calf crisis. Jesus: Transfiguration glory → demoniac crisis. But Jesus succeeds where Moses'' patience failed — He heals the boy and teaches the disciples, demonstrating greater authority and compassion.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 18 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 18, 'kids', 1, 'Who did Jesus say is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven?', 'Whoever humbles himself like a little child', 'The richest person', 'The strongest warrior', 'The oldest teacher', 'a', 'Matthew 18:4 — "Whosoever therefore shall humble himself as this little child, the same is greatest in the kingdom of heaven."'),
('Matthew', 18, 'kids', 2, 'In Jesus'' story about the lost sheep, how many sheep did the shepherd leave to go find the one that was lost?', 'Ninety-nine', 'Fifty', 'Ten', 'Five hundred', 'a', 'Matthew 18:12 — "If a man have an hundred sheep, and one of them be gone astray, doth he not leave the ninety and nine, and goeth into the mountains, and seeketh that which is gone astray?"'),
('Matthew', 18, 'kids', 3, 'How many times did Jesus say we should forgive someone?', 'Seventy times seven', 'Only one time', 'Three times', 'Seven times', 'a', 'Matthew 18:22 — "Jesus saith unto him, I say not unto thee, Until seven times: but, Until seventy times seven."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 18, 'teens', 1, 'What serious warning did Jesus give about causing a child or a believer to sin?', 'It would be better for him to have a millstone hanged about his neck and be drowned in the depth of the sea', 'He would receive a small fine', 'Nothing would happen to him', 'He would miss one day of worship', 'a', 'Matthew 18:6 — "But whoso shall offend one of these little ones which believe in me, it were better for him that a millstone were hanged about his neck, and that he were drowned in the depth of the sea."'),
('Matthew', 18, 'teens', 2, 'What three steps did Jesus outline for dealing with a brother who sins against you?', 'First go and tell him his fault privately; if he does not listen, take one or two witnesses; if he still refuses, tell it to the church', 'Ignore it and hope it goes away', 'Immediately tell everyone about it', 'Report it to the Roman authorities', 'a', 'Matthew 18:15-17 — "Moreover if thy brother shall trespass against thee, go and tell him his fault between thee and him alone: if he shall hear thee, thou hast gained thy brother. But if he will not hear thee, then take with thee one or two more... And if he shall neglect to hear them, tell it unto the church."'),
('Matthew', 18, 'teens', 3, 'What did Jesus promise about two or three gathered in His name?', 'For where two or three are gathered together in my name, there am I in the midst of them', 'They will automatically become wealthy', 'They will receive two or three gifts', 'They should meet only in the temple', 'a', 'Matthew 18:20 — "For where two or three are gathered together in my name, there am I in the midst of them."'),
('Matthew', 18, 'teens', 4, 'In the parable of the unforgiving servant, what happened to the servant who refused to forgive?', 'His master delivered him to the tormentors until he should pay all that was due — because he would not forgive his fellow servant''s small debt after being forgiven an enormous debt himself', 'His master praised him for being strict', 'Nothing happened because he was the king''s favourite', 'He was promoted to a higher position', 'a', 'Matthew 18:34 — "And his lord was wroth, and delivered him to the tormentors, till he should pay all that was due unto him."'),
('Matthew', 18, 'teens', 5, 'How much did the first servant owe the king in the parable?', 'Ten thousand talents — an impossibly enormous sum representing an unpayable debt', 'One hundred pence — a small amount', 'Ten silver coins', 'One gold coin', 'a', 'Matthew 18:24 — "One was brought unto him, which owed him ten thousand talents." Ten thousand talents was the largest number (myrioi) and the largest unit of currency, representing an astronomical, unpayable debt.'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 1, 'How does the child illustration (18:1-5) redefine greatness in the kingdom?', 'In a culture where children had no status, rights, or social power, Jesus uses a child as the model of kingdom greatness. The point is not childish naivety but childlike dependence, humility, and lack of social ambition. Kingdom greatness is inversely proportional to self-importance — the humblest is the greatest', 'Children were powerful in ancient society', 'Jesus valued childish behaviour in adults', 'The child was a metaphor for physical smallness', 'a', 'Matthew 18:3-4 — "Except ye be converted, and become as little children, ye shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven. Whosoever therefore shall humble himself as this little child." Children in first-century culture had zero social leverage. Jesus turns the status hierarchy upside down: lowliness, not ambition, defines greatness.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 2, 'What does the three-step discipline process (18:15-17) establish about church governance and community accountability?', 'Jesus establishes a progressive, grace-filled process: (1) private confrontation preserving dignity; (2) small group witnesses ensuring fairness (cf. Deuteronomy 19:15); (3) church community involvement for accountability. The goal is always restoration ("thou hast gained thy brother"), not punishment. Only after all attempts fail does separation occur', 'Sinners should be expelled immediately', 'Private sin should be publicly announced first', 'The church has no authority to discipline', 'a', 'Matthew 18:15-17 — The sequence is: private → small group → community. Each step expands the circle only as necessary. The goal at every stage is reconciliation: "if he shall hear thee, thou hast gained thy brother." Excommunication ("let him be unto thee as an heathen man") is the last resort, not the first response.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 3, 'What does the parable of the unforgiving servant (18:21-35) teach about the relationship between divine and human forgiveness?', 'The ten thousand talents (billions in modern currency) vs. one hundred pence (a few dollars) illustrates the infinite disproportion between God''s forgiveness of us and our forgiveness of others. Anyone who has truly experienced God''s mercy will naturally extend mercy. Refusal to forgive reveals that one has not genuinely grasped grace', 'Human forgiveness earns divine forgiveness', 'The parable teaches that forgiveness has limits', 'The two debts are roughly equivalent', 'a', 'Matthew 18:32-33 — "I forgave thee all that debt... shouldest not thou also have had compassion on thy fellowservant, even as I had pity on thee?" The ratio is extreme: 10,000 talents vs. 100 denarii = roughly 600,000:1. Our debts against each other are trivial compared to our debt before God.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 4, 'What does "where two or three are gathered together in my name, there am I in the midst of them" mean in context?', 'In context, this promise relates to church discipline and prayer for reconciliation (vv.15-19), not merely small group worship. Jesus promises His authoritative presence when the community gathers to address sin, pray for unity, and make binding decisions. "In my name" means according to His character and will, not merely using His name as an invocation', 'This applies only to worship services', 'Jesus is physically present wherever three Christians meet', 'The verse has nothing to do with church discipline', 'a', 'Matthew 18:20 — Read in context, "two or three" connects to the "two or three witnesses" of verse 16 and the "two of you shall agree" of verse 19. Jesus'' presence guarantees that Spirit-led community decisions carry heavenly authority (v.18). The promise is about authoritative kingdom presence, not mere companionship.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 5, 'What does the lost sheep parable in this context (vs. Luke 15''s context) specifically teach?', 'In Luke 15, the lost sheep parable defends Jesus'' ministry to sinners against Pharisaic criticism. In Matthew 18, the same parable teaches the church not to despise or neglect "little ones" — vulnerable believers who wander. The application shifts from evangelistic seeking (Luke) to pastoral care (Matthew). "It is not the will of your Father... that one of these little ones should perish"', 'The two versions teach identical lessons', 'Only Luke''s version is authentic', 'Matthew added the parable accidentally', 'a', 'Matthew 18:12-14 — "If a man have an hundred sheep, and one of them be gone astray... it is not the will of your Father which is in heaven, that one of these little ones should perish." In Matthew''s pastoral context (church community), the parable urges care for wandering believers — the church must pursue, not abandon, those who stray.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 6, 'Why does Jesus say "seventy times seven" in response to Peter''s question about forgiving seven times?', 'Peter thought seven was generous (rabbis taught forgiving three times). Jesus'' "seventy times seven" (490 times) is not a literal limit but a symbolic expression of unlimited forgiveness — reversing Lamech''s seventy-sevenfold vengeance (Genesis 4:24). Grace replaces revenge; forgiveness has no ceiling', 'Jesus meant exactly 490 times', 'Peter''s suggestion of seven was too many', 'Forgiveness should stop after three times', 'a', 'Matthew 18:21-22 — "Until seventy times seven." In Genesis 4:24, Lamech boasted of seventy-sevenfold revenge. Jesus inverts the principle: where sin multiplied revenge, grace multiplies forgiveness. The number is not a cap but a symbol: forgiveness is unlimited because God''s forgiveness of us is unlimited.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 7, 'What does the millstone warning (18:6) teach about the gravity of spiritual harm to vulnerable believers?', 'The millstone (mulon onikon — a massive stone turned by a donkey, not a hand-mill) and drowning in the "depth of the sea" represent the worst physical fate imaginable. Jesus says even this is preferable to causing a believer to stumble — implying that the spiritual consequence (hell, v.8-9) is infinitely worse than the most horrific physical death', 'The millstone is a light punishment', 'Jesus was exaggerating to make a point', 'Only hurting children physically triggers this warning', 'a', 'Matthew 18:6 — "It were better for him that a millstone (mulon onikon) were hanged about his neck, and that he were drowned in the depth of the sea." The donkey-driven millstone was the heaviest common object. Better to die the most horrific death than to face God''s judgment for leading a believer into sin.'),
('Matthew', 18, 'adults', 8, 'How does Matthew 18 as a whole function as Jesus'' discourse on community life (the fourth of five discourses)?', 'Chapter 18 is the Discourse on Community, addressing how kingdom citizens relate within the church: humility (vv.1-5), not causing stumbling (vv.6-9), pursuing the wandering (vv.10-14), resolving conflict (vv.15-20), and unlimited forgiveness (vv.21-35). It moves from individual character to communal responsibility, painting a picture of a grace-shaped community', 'Chapter 18 has no unifying theme', 'It is only about children', 'It is mainly about judgment', 'a', 'Matthew 18 — The discourse unfolds logically: enter the kingdom like a child (humility) → protect the vulnerable (not causing stumbling) → pursue the wandering (lost sheep) → resolve conflict (discipline process) → forgive without limit (unforgiving servant). Every section builds a vision of a community defined by grace, humility, and restoration.');
